title.narrative: Title II Development Food Security Activity (DFSA) - FH

description.narrative: (Ethiopia): .Food for the Hungry (FH) Ethiopia Development Food Security.Activity (DFSA) supports the Ethiopian Government led Productive Safety Net Program.(PSNP) in seven districts of Amhara region to improve food security and.increase household resilience to shocks, thereby decreasing their reliance on.USG assistance. FH's integrated activities contribute to the Mission's CDCS.(Development Objective 2) and the Development Food Security strategy of the.Bureau of Humanitarian Assistance (BHA). ..With FY 2020 funds, a total of 16,903 MT of food and.$2,356,918 cash will be distributed to 221,893 beneficiaries to cover their.food gaps. FH will continue supporting the management of watershed and natural.resource conservation, constructing 21 different types of soil and water.conservation structures and 9,000 hectares of land will be enclosed. FH.will produce and plant 21 million forest trees and fodder seedlings. FH DFSA.increases and diversifies livelihoods and incomes to beneficiaries through.provision of high-quality seeds, small ruminants, and high-value crop seeds.that is complemented with coaching and mentoring support and linkages to.finance. A total of 39 small scale water structures for irrigation will be.completed to improve production and productivity on 108 hectares of land and.benefit 324 HHs. Approximately 1,460 clients will receive livelihood.package transfers. FH will support 20,700 participants to have access to.weather, input supply, and market price information. Training on.nutrition-sensitive agriculture will continue so that farmers can grow.vegetables to diversify nutrition for children, pregnant and lactating women..Implementing partners will promote WASH, construct 12 water schemes, and.deliver appropriate training. In addition, COVID-19 related activities will.continue, including awareness-raising and the provision of handwashing.facilities and hand sanitizers at all food distribution centers..... ...
